                    <note>Fiey provides the following bibliographic citations: <quote source="#bib13-2">Saint Ephrem est celebre par les Syriaques le 28 janvier.
La bibliographie sur Ephrem est immense; v. K. den Biesen, Bibliography of Ephrem
the Syrian (Giove in Umbria, 2002). La meilleure etude sur "Saint Ephrem d'apres
sa biographie et ses ceuvres", me semble etre celle de Dom B. Outier dans PdO 4
(1973), 12-53. V. aussi J. Amer, "Byzantine Ascetic Monachism and Greek Bias
in the Vita Tradition of Ephrem the Syrian", OCP 58 (1992), 123-58.
Surles rapports de saint Ephrem avec les eveques de Nisibe, cf. J.M. Fiey, Nisibe,
123-35.
S.P. Brock, The Luminous Eye : the Spiritual World Vision of St Ephrem the Syrian.
Kalamazoo, 1992.
BS, IV, 944-49 (J.-M. Sauget).</quote>
                    </note>
                    <note type="abstract">Ephrem the Syrian is a doctor of the church and theologian. He was the author of hymns, homilies, and prose, and his fourth-century writings reflect a Golden Age of Syriac literature. His Vita differs greatly from the Ephrem of history.  The Vita, which transforms him into Byzantine monk, was nevertheless a tribute to his importance, in both the Syriac and Byzantine Greek churches.</note>
                    <note type="disambiguation">Ephrem the Syrian</note>
